    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense as a theoretical point. But does that argument hold up when you look at how much of that \"innovation\" is actually just acquiring competitors before they can grow? It feels like the regulators are essentially trying to decide if the current model is sustainable in the long run, or if it's just a dead end for new startups. Do you think the current legal framework is actually equipped to handle this, or is the system fundamentally lagging behind how these platforms work?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The core issue is that the existing legal framework, designed for 20th-century industrial monopolies, is inherently ill-equipped to police dynamic, platform-based digital markets. The constant acquisition of nascent competitors, often termed \"killer acquisitions,\" is a direct manifestation of this structural lag, as current laws struggle to define when growth becomes anti-competitive. Therefore, regulators are not just assessing sustainability; they are grappling with how to apply outdated concepts of market power to entirely new forms of digital control.",
      "source": "target",
